### Step 4: Apply the LIX Formula
The LIX formula is:

\[
\text{LIX} = \left( \frac{\text{Number of Words}}{\text{Number of Sentences}} \right) + \left( \frac{\text{Number of Long Words} \times 100}{\text{Number of Words}} \right)
\]

Plugging in the values:

\[
\text{LIX} = \left( \frac{19}{1} \right) + \left( \frac{6 \times 100}{19} \right) = 19 + \frac{600}{19} \approx 19 + 31.58 = 50.58
\]

However, reviewing the calculation shows a mistake in the final addition step. The correct calculation should be:

\[
\frac{600}{19} \approx 31.58 \\
\text{LIX} = 19 + 31.58 = 50.58
\]

But considering typical LIX scores and re-evaluating the long words count might be necessary. If we adhere strictly to the initial counting:

